#. type: Title -
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:131
#, no-wrap
msgid "KiCad work-flow"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:137
msgid ""
"Despite its similarities with other PCB software tools, KiCad is "
"characterised by an interesting work-flow in which schematic components and "
"footprints are actually two separate entities. This is often the subject of "
"discussion on Internet forums."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:143
msgid ""
"The KiCad work-flow is comprised of two main tasks: making the schematic and "
"laying out the board. Both a components library and a footprints library are "
"necessary for these two tasks. KiCad has plenty of both.  Just in case that "
"is not enough, KiCad also has the tools necessary to make new ones."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:145
msgid ""
"image:images/10000000000004DD000002BDCE77181D."
"png[10000000000004DD000002BDCE77181D_png]"
msgstr ""
"image:images/10000000000004DD000002BDCE77181D."
"png[10000000000004DD000002BDCE77181D_png]"

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:150
msgid ""
"In the picture above, the greyed out blocks indicate component-drawing and "
"footprint-drawing tools that are not strictly part of KiCad.  However, since "
"they are all very valuable options, do not forget to check them out. You can "
"find some at this address:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:152
msgid "http://kicad.rohrbacher.net/quicklib.php"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:157
msgid ""
"On this site, you will find an example of a tool that allows you to quickly "
"create a KiCad library component. For more information about quicklib, refer "
"to the section of this document titled __Make Schematic Component With "
"quicklib__."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ~
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:160
#, no-wrap
msgid "Forward and backward annotation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:168
msgid ""
"Once an electronic schematic has been fully drawn, the next step is to "
"transfer it to a PCB following the KiCad work-flow. Once the board layout "
"process has been partially or completely done, additional components or nets "
"might need to be added, parts moved around and much more. This can be done "
"in two ways: Backward Annotation and Forward Annotation."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:172
msgid ""
"Backward Annotation is the process of sending a PCB layout change back to "
"its corresponding schematic. Some do not consider this particular feature "
"especially useful."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:178
msgid ""
"Forward Annotation is the process of sending schematic changes to a "
"corresponding PCB layout. This is a fundamental feature because you do not "
"really want to re-do the layout of the whole PCB every time you make a "
"modification to your schematic. Forward Annotation is discussed in the "
"section titled __Forward Annotation__."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title -
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:181
#, no-wrap
msgid "Draw electronic schematics"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:185
msgid ""
"In this section we are going to learn how to draw an electronic schematic "
"using KiCad."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:192
msgid ""
"Under Windows run kicad.exe. Under Linux type kicad in your Terminal. You "
"are now in the main window of the KiCad project manager.  From here you have "
"access to five stand-alone software tools: __EESchema__, __Cvpcb__, "
"__PCBnew__, _GerbView_ and __Bitmap2Component__. Refer to the work-flow "
"chart for an idea of what all these tools are used for."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:194
msgid "image:images/kicad_main_window.png[kicad_main_window_png]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:199
msgid ""
"Create a new project: *File* -> **New**. Click on the 'New Folder' button, "
"and give your new folder the same name as your project: 'tute1'.  Open the "
"new folder by double clicking on it. All your project files will be saved "
"here. Name the project file 'tute1'. The project file will automatically "
"take the extension .pro."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:203
msgid ""
"Let's begin by creating a schematic. Start the schematic editor "
"__EESchema__, image:images/eeschema.png[eeschema_png]. It is the first "
"button from the left. If an error dialogue appears telling you that a "
"project file was not found, ignore it and click OK."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:210
msgid ""
"First thing, save the whole schematic project: *File* -> **Save Whole "
"Schematic Project**. Click on the 'Page Settings' icon image:images/sheetset."
"png[sheetset_png] on the top toolbar. Set the Page Size as 'A4' and enter "
"the Title as 'Tute 1'. You will see that more information can be entered "
"here if necessary. Click OK. This information will populate the schematic "
"sheet at the bottom right corner. Use the mouse wheel to zoom in."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:215
msgid ""
"We will now place our first component. Click on the 'Add components' icon "
"image:images/100002010000001A0000001ACFBFFF00."
"png[100002010000001A0000001ACFBFFF00_png] in the right toolbar. The same "
"functionality is achieved by pressing the 'Add components' shortcut a key."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:221
msgid ""
"You can see a list of all available shortcut keys by pressing the ? key. "
"Click in the middle of your schematic sheet to place your first component. "
"The Component Selection window will appear. Click on the 'List All' button. "
"The Select Library window will appear. Here you have a list of all available "
"libraries."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:225
msgid ""
"Select the 'device' library by double clicking on it. The Select Component "
"window will appear. Here you have a list of components belonging to the "
"'device' library, which is a quite generic and useful library."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:227
msgid ""
"Scroll down and double click on the resistor 'R'. This will close the "
"'Select Component' window and take you back to your schematic sheet."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:231
msgid ""
"Place the component in the schematic sheet by clicking where you want it to "
"be. Click on the magnifier to zoom in on the component.  Alternatively, use "
"the mouse wheel to zoom in and zoom out.  Unfortunately, the panning option "
"has not yet been implemented."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:233
msgid ""
"Hover the mouse over the component 'R' and press the r key. Notice how the "
"component rotates."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:235
msgid "You do not need to actually click on the component to rotate it."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:240
msgid ""
"Right click in the middle of the component and select *Edit Component* -> "
"**Value**. You can achieve the same result by hovering over the component "
"and pressing the v key. Alternatively, the e key will take you to the more "
"general Edit window. Notice how the right-click window below shows all "
"possible shortcut keys for all available actions."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:242
msgid ""
"image:images/100000000000026B000001BD635CBA2F."
"png[100000000000026B000001BD635CBA2F_png]"
msgstr ""
"image:images/100000000000026B000001BD635CBA2F."
"png[100000000000026B000001BD635CBA2F_png]"

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:244
msgid ""
"The Component value window will appear. Replace the current value 'R' with "
"'1k'. Click OK."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:248
msgid ""
"Do not change the Reference field (R?), this will be done automatically "
"later on. The value inside the resistor should now be '1k'."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:250
msgid ""
"image:images/10000000000000B0000000463CCB103A."
"png[10000000000000B0000000463CCB103A_png]"
msgstr ""
"image:images/10000000000000B0000000463CCB103A."
"png[10000000000000B0000000463CCB103A_png]"

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:252
msgid ""
"To place another resistor, simply click where you want the resistor to "
"appear. The Component Selection window will appear again."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:254
msgid ""
"The resistor you previously chose is now in your history list, appearing as "
"'R'. Click OK and place the component."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:256
msgid ""
"image:images/100000000000016C000000E147EEA45E."
"png[100000000000016C000000E147EEA45E_png]"
msgstr ""
"image:images/100000000000016C000000E147EEA45E."
"png[100000000000016C000000E147EEA45E_png]"

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:260
msgid ""
"In case you make a mistake and want to delete a component, right click on "
"the component and click 'Delete Component'. This will remove the component "
"from the schematic. Alternatively, you can hover over the component you want "
"to delete and press the del key."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:264
msgid ""
"You can rename any default shortcut key by going to *Preferences* -> "
"**Hotkeys**. Do not forget to save the new keys with *Preferences* -> **Save "
"preferences**."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:267
msgid ""
"You can also duplicate a component already on your schematic sheet by "
"hovering over it and pressing the c key. Click where you want to place the "
"new duplicated component."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:272
msgid ""
"Right click on the second resistor. Select 'Drag Component'.  Reposition the "
"component and left click to drop. The same functionality can be achieved by "
"hovering over the component and by pressing the g key. Use the r key to "
"rotate the component. The x key and the y key will flip the component."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:277
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"*Right-Click* -> *Move component* (equivalent to the m key option)\n"
"is also a valuable option for moving anything around, but it is better\n"
"to use this only for component labels and components yet to be\n"
"connected. We will see later on why this is the case.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:280
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Edit the second resistor by hovering over it and pressing the v key.\n"
"Replace 'R' with '100'. You can undo any of your editing actions with\n"
"the ctrl+z key.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:285
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Change the grid size. You have probably noticed that on the\n"
"schematic sheet all components are snapped onto a large pitch grid. You\n"
"can easily change the size of the grid by *Right-Click* -> **Grid\n"
"select**. __In general, it is recommendable to use a grid of 25.0 mils\n"
"for the schematic sheet__.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:288
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Repeat the add-component steps, however this time select the\n"
"'microcontrollers' library instead of the 'device' library and pick the\n"
"'PIC12C508A' component instead of the 'R' component from it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:292
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Hover the mouse over the microcontroller component. Press the y key\n"
"or the x key on the keyboard. Notice how the component is flipped over\n"
"its x axis or its y axis. Press the key again to return it to its\n"
"original orientation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:294
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Repeat the add-component steps, this time choosing the 'device'\n"
"library and picking the 'LED' component from it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:295
#, no-wrap
msgid "Organise all components on your schematic sheet as shown below.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:297
#, no-wrap
msgid "image:images/1000000000000279000001D2A3715F27.png[1000000000000279000001D2A3715F27_png]\n"
msgstr "image:images/1000000000000279000001D2A3715F27.png[1000000000000279000001D2A3715F27_png]\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:301
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"We now need to create the schematic component 'MYCONN3' for our\n"
"3-pin connector. You can jump to the section titled _Make a Schematic\n"
"Component in KiCad_ to learn how to make this component from scratch and\n"
"then return to this section to continue with the board.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:303
#, no-wrap
msgid "-> _jump to the section: Make a Schematic Component in KiCad_\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:306
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You can now place the freshly made component. Press the a key and\n"
"select 'List All'. Choose the library 'myLib' and pick the component\n"
"'MYCONN3'.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:311
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The component identifier 'J?' will appear under the 'MYCONN3' label.\n"
"If you want to change its position, right click on 'J?' and click on\n"
"'Move Field' (equivalent to the m key option). It might be helpful to\n"
"zoom in before/while doing this. Reposition 'J?' under the component as\n"
"shown below. Labels can be moved around as many times as you please.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:313
#, no-wrap
msgid "image:images/10000000000000950000007B843ADE6A.png[10000000000000950000007B843ADE6A_png]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:319
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"It is time to place the power and ground symbols. Click on the\n"
"'Place a power port' button image:images/add_power.png[add_power_png] on\n"
"the right toolbar. Alternatively, press the a key and choose the 'power'\n"
"library. In the component selection window, click on the 'List All'\n"
"button. Scroll down and select 'VCC' from the Select Component window.\n"
"Click OK.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:324
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Click above the pin of the 1k resistor to place the VCC part. Click\n"
"on the area above the microcontroller 'VDD'. In the 'Component Selection\n"
"history' section select 'VCC' and place it next to the VDD pin. Repeat\n"
"the add process again and place a VCC part above the VCC pin of\n"
"'MYCONN3'.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:328
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Repeat the add-pin steps but this time select the GND part. Place a\n"
"GND part under the GND pin of 'MYCONN3'. Place another GND symbol on the\n"
"right of the VSS pin of the microcontroller. Your schematic should now\n"
"look something like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:330
#, no-wrap
msgid "image:images/1000000000000303000002A0130916D9.png[1000000000000303000002A0130916D9_png]\n"
msgstr "image:images/1000000000000303000002A0130916D9.png[1000000000000303000002A0130916D9_png]\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:337
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Next, we will wire all our components. Click on the 'Place a wire'\n"
"icon\n"
"image:images/100002010000001A0000001A10CC204F.png[100002010000001A0000001A10CC204F_png]\n"
"on the right toolbar. **NOTE**: Be careful not to pick 'Place a bus',\n"
"which appears directly beneath this button but has thicker lines. The\n"
"section _Bus Connections in KiCad_ will explain how to use a bus\n"
"section.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:340
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Click on the little circle at the end of pin 7 of the\n"
"microcontroller and then click on the little circle on pin 2 of the LED.\n"
"You can zoom in while you are placing the connection.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:345
msgid ""
"If you want to reposition wired components, it is important to use the g key "
"(grab) option and not the m key (move) option. Using the grab option will "
"keep the wires connected. Review step 24 in case you have forgotten how to "
"move a component."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:347
msgid ""
"image:images/1000000000000134000000D9A9B4ED54."
"png[1000000000000134000000D9A9B4ED54_png]"
msgstr ""
"image:images/1000000000000134000000D9A9B4ED54."
"png[1000000000000134000000D9A9B4ED54_png]"

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:351
msgid ""
"Repeat this process and wire up all the other components as shown below. To "
"terminate a wire just double-click. When wiring up the VCC and GND symbols, "
"the wire should touch the bottom of the VCC symbol and the middle top of the "
"GND symbol. See the screenshot below."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:353
msgid ""
"image:images/100000000000033200000294961F4BAD."
"png[100000000000033200000294961F4BAD_png]"
msgstr ""
"image:images/100000000000033200000294961F4BAD."
"png[100000000000033200000294961F4BAD_png]"

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:357
msgid ""
"We will now consider an alternative way of making a connection using labels. "
"Pick a net labelling tool by clicking on the 'Place net name' icon image:"
"images/label.png[label_png] on the right toolbar. You can also use the l key."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:359
msgid ""
"Click in the middle of the wire connected to pin 6 of the microcontroller. "
"Name this label 'INPUT'."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:366
msgid ""
"Follow the same procedure and place another label on line on the right of "
"the 100 ohm resistor. Also name it 'INPUT'. The two labels, having the same "
"name, create an invisible connection between pin 6 of the PIC and the 100 "
"ohm resistor. This is a useful technique when connecting wires in a complex "
"design where drawing the lines would make the whole schematic messier. To "
"place a label you do not necessarily need a wire, you can simply attach the "
"label to a pin."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:370
msgid ""
"Labels can also be used to simply label wires for informative purposes. "
"Place a label on pin 7 of the PIC. Enter the name 'uCtoLED'.  Name the wire "
"between the resistor and the LED as 'LEDtoR'. Name the wire between "
"'MYCONN3' and the resistor as 'INPUTtoR'."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:372
msgid ""
"You do not have to label the VCC and GND lines because the labels are "
"implied from the power objects they are connected to."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:373
msgid "Below you can see what the final result should look like."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:375
msgid ""
"image:images/1000000000000340000002A2DDE0F6DA."
"png[1000000000000340000002A2DDE0F6DA_png]"
msgstr ""
"image:images/1000000000000340000002A2DDE0F6DA."
"png[1000000000000340000002A2DDE0F6DA_png]"

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:380
msgid ""
"Let's now deal with unconnected wires. Any pin or wire that is not connected "
"will generate a warning when checked by KiCad. To avoid these warnings you "
"can either instruct the program that the unconnected wires are deliberate or "
"manually flag each unconnected wire or pin as unconnected."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:384
msgid ""
"Click on the 'Place no connect flag' icon image:images/noconn."
"png[noconn_png] on the right toolbar. Click on pins 2, 3, 4 and 5. An X will "
"appear to signify that the lack of a wire connection is intentional."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:386
msgid ""
"image:images/10000000000001C8000000FEEDCB5FB8."
"png[10000000000001C8000000FEEDCB5FB8_png]"
msgstr ""
"image:images/10000000000001C8000000FEEDCB5FB8."
"png[10000000000001C8000000FEEDCB5FB8_png]"

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:392
msgid ""
"Some components have power pins that are invisible. You can make them "
"visible by clicking on the 'Show hidden pins' icon image:images/hidden_pin."
"png[hidden_pin_png] on the left toolbar. Hidden power pins get automatically "
"connected if VCC and GNS naming is respected. Generally speaking, you should "
"try not to make hidden power pins."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:396
msgid ""
"It is now necessary to add a 'Power Flag' to indicate to KiCad that power "
"comes in from somewhere. Press the a key, select 'List All', double click on "
"the 'power' library and search for 'PWR_FLAG'. Place two of them. Connect "
"them to a GND pin and to VCC as shown below."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:398
msgid ""
"image:images/100000000000010700000125A4376EBB."
"png[100000000000010700000125A4376EBB_png]"
msgstr ""
"image:images/100000000000010700000125A4376EBB."
"png[100000000000010700000125A4376EBB_png]"

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:401
msgid ""
"This will avoid the classic schematic checking warning: Warning Pin power_in "
"not driven (Net xx)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:404
msgid ""
"Sometimes it is good to write comments here and there. To add comments on "
"the schematic use the 'Place graphic text (comment)' icon image:images/"
"add_text.png[add_text_png] on the right toolbar."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:408
msgid ""
"All components now need to have unique identifiers. In fact, many of our "
"components are still named 'R?' or 'J?'. Identifier assignation can be done "
"automatically by clicking on the 'Annotate schematic' icon image:images/"
"annotate.png[annotate_png]."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:413
msgid ""
"In the Annotate Schematic window, select 'Use the entire schematic' and "
"click on the 'Annotation' button. Click OK in the confirmation message and "
"then click 'Close'. Notice how all the '?' have been replaced with numbers. "
"Each identifier is now unique. In our example, they have been named 'R1', "
"'R2', 'U1', 'D1' and 'J1'."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:421
msgid ""
"We will now check our schematic for errors. Click on the 'Perform Electric "
"Rules Check' icon image:images/erc.png[erc_png]. Click on the 'Test ERC' "
"button. A report informing you of any errors or warnings such as "
"disconnected wires is generated. You should have 0 Errors and 0 Warnings. In "
"case of errors or warnings, a small green arrow will appear on the schematic "
"in the position where the error or the warning is located. Check 'Write ERC "
"report' and press the 'Test ERC' button again to receive more information "
"about the errors."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:426
msgid ""
"The schematic is now finished. We can now create a Netlist file to which we "
"will add the footprint of each component. Click on the 'Netlist generation' "
"icon image:images/netlist.png[netlist_png] on the top toolbar. Click on "
"'Netlist' then click on 'save'. Save under the default file name."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:430
msgid ""
"You can now quit the schematic editor. From KiCad, click on the 'Run Cvpcb' "
"icon image:images/icon_cvpcb_small.png[icon_cvpcb_small_png] on the top "
"toolbar. If a missing file error window pops up, just ignore it and click OK."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:435
msgid ""
"_Cvpcb_ allows you to link all the components in your schematic with "
"footprints in the KiCad library. The pane on the left shows all the "
"components used in your schematic. Here select 'D1'. In the pane on the "
"right you have all the available footprints, here scroll down to 'LEDV' and "
"double click on it. image:images/cvpcb.png[cvpcb_png]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:440
msgid ""
"It is possible that the pane on the right shows only a selected subgroup of "
"available footprints. This is because KiCad is trying to suggest to you a "
"subset of suitable footprints. Click on the icon image:images/"
"module_full_list.png[module_full_list_png] to deselect this filter."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:442
msgid ""
"For 'J1' select the '3PIN_6mm' footprint. For 'R1' and 'R2' select the 'R1' "
"footprint. Select 'DIP-8_300' for 'U1'."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:450
msgid ""
"If you are interested in knowing what the footprint you are choosing looks "
"like, you have two options. You can click on the 'View selected footprint' "
"icon image:images/show_footprint.png[show_footprint_png] for a preview of "
"the current footprint. Alternatively, click on the 'Display footprint list "
"documentation' icon image:images/datasheet.png[datasheet_png] and you will "
"get a multi-page PDF document with all available footprints. You can print "
"it out and check your components to make sure that the dimensions match."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:458
msgid ""
"You are done. You can now update your netlist file with all the associated "
"footprints. Click on *File* -> **Save As**. The default name 'tute1.net' is "
"fine, click save. Otherwise you can use the icon image:"
"images/100002010000001A0000001AF4CF46A1."
"png[100002010000001A0000001AF4CF46A1_png].  Your netlist file has now been "
"updated with all the footprints. Note that if you are missing the footprint "
"of any device, you will need to make your own footprints. This will be "
"explained in a later section of this document."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:461
msgid ""
"You can close _Cvpcb_ and go back to the _EESchema_ schematic editor. Save "
"the project by clicking on *File* -> **Save Whole Schematic Project**. Close "
"the schematic editor."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:462
msgid "Switch to the KiCad project manager."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:465
msgid ""
"The netlist file describes all components and their respective pin "
"connections. The netlist file is actually a text file that you can easily "
"inspect, edit or script."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:468
msgid ""
"Library files (__*.lib__) are text files too and they are also easily "
"editable or scriptable."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:471
msgid ""
"To create a bill of materials, go to the _EESchema_ schematic editor and "
"click on the 'Bill of materials' icon image:images/bom.png[bom_png] on the "
"top toolbar."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:473
msgid ""
"Click OK and then 'Save'. You can inspect the bill of materials with any "
"text editor."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:477
msgid ""
"You are now ready to move to the PCB layout part, which is presented in the "
"next section. However, before moving on let's take a quick look at how to "
"connect component pins using a bus line."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ~
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:480
#, no-wrap
msgid "Bus connections in KiCad"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:486
msgid ""
"Sometimes you might need to connect several sequential pins of component A "
"with some other sequential pins of component B. In this case you have two "
"options: the labelling method we already saw or the use of a bus connection. "
"Let's see how to do it."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:492
msgid ""
"Let us suppose that you have three 4-pin connectors that you want to connect "
"together pin to pin. Use the label option (press the l key) to label pin 4 "
"of the P4 part. Name this label 'a1'. Now let's press the Ins key to have "
"the same action automatically performed on the pin below pin 4 (PIN 3). "
"Notice how the label is automatically renamed 'a2'."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:495
msgid ""
"Press the Ins Key two more times. The Ins key corresponds to the action "
"'Repeat last action' and it is an infinitely useful command that can make "
"your life a lot easier."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:505
msgid ""
"Repeat the same labelling action on the two other connectors CONN_2 and "
"CONN_3 and you are done. If you proceed and make a PCB you will see that the "
"three connectors are connected to each other. Figure 2 shows the result of "
"what we described. For aesthetic purposes it is also possible to add a "
"series of 'Wire to bus entry' using the icon image:"
"images/100000000000001C0000001CA8839A4E."
"png[100000000000001C0000001CA8839A4E_png] and bus line using the icon image:"
"images/100000000000001C0000001C232C9272."
"png[100000000000001C0000001C232C9272_png], as shown in Figure 3. Mind, "
"however, that there will be no effect on the PCB."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:508
msgid ""
"It should be pointed out that the short wire attached to the pins in Figure "
"2 is not strictly necessary. In fact, the labels could have been applied "
"directly to the pins."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:514
msgid ""
"Let's take it one step further and suppose that you have a fourth connector "
"named CONN_4 and, for whatever reason, its labelling happens to be a little "
"different (b1, b2, b3, b4). Now we want to connect _Bus a_ with _Bus b_ in a "
"pin to pin manner. We want to do that without using pin labelling (which is "
"also possible) but by instead using labelling on the bus line, with one "
"label per bus."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:519
msgid ""
"Connect and label CONN_4 using the labelling method explained before. Name "
"the pins b1, b2, b3 and b4. Connect the pin to a series of 'Wire to bus "
"entry' using the icon image:images/add_line2bus.png[add_line2bus_png] and to "
"a bus line using the icon image:images/add_bus.png[add_bus_png]. See Figure "
"4."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:521
msgid ""
"Put a label (press the l key option) on the bus of CONN_4 and name it "
"'b[1..4]'."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:523
msgid ""
"Put a label (press the l key option) on the previous a bus and name it "
"'a[1..4]'."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:525
msgid ""
"What we can now do is connect bus a[1..4] with bus b[1..4] using a bus line "
"with the button image:images/add_bus.png[add_bus_png]."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:532
msgid ""
"By connecting the two buses together, pin a1 will be automatically connected "
"to pin b1, a2 will be connected to b2 and so on. Figure 4 shows what the "
"final result looks like. NOTE: The 'Repeat last action' option accessible "
"via the Ins key can be successfully used to repeat period actions. For "
"instance, the short wires connected to all pins in Figure 2, Figure 3 and "
"Figure 4 have been placed with this option. Learn how to use it because it "
"will make using KiCad easier."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:536
msgid ""
"The 'Repeat last action' option accessible via the Ins key has also been "
"extensively used to place the many series of 'Wire to bus entry' using the "
"icon image:images/add_line2bus.png[add_line2bus_png].  image:"
"images/10000000000004A2000001E05B3D8DFF."
"png[10000000000004A2000001E05B3D8DFF_png]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title -
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:539
#, no-wrap
msgid "Layout printed circuit boards"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:543
msgid ""
"It is now time to use the netlist file you generated to lay out the PCB.  "
"This is done with the _PCBnew_ tool."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:548
msgid ""
"From the KiCad project manager, click on the 'PCBNew' icon image:images/"
"pcbnew.png[pcbnew_png]. The 'PCBNew' window will open. If you get an error "
"message saying that a _.brg_ file does not exist just ignore it and click OK."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:551
msgid ""
"Begin by entering some schematic information. Click on the 'Page settings' "
"icon image:images/sheetset.png[sheetset_png] on the top toolbar. Set 'paper "
"size' as 'A4' and 'title' as 'Tute 1'."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:558
msgid ""
"It is a good idea to start by setting the *clearance* and the *minimum track "
"width* to those required by your PCB manufacturer. In general you can set "
"the clearance to 0.015' and the minimum track width to 0.01'. Click on the "
"*Design Rules* -> *Design Rules* menu. If it does not show already, click on "
"the 'Net Classes Editor' tab. Change the 'Clearance' field at the top of the "
"window to '0.015' and the 'Track Width' field to '0.01' as shown below. "
"Measurements here are in inches."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:560
msgid ""
"image:images/10000000000001600000004C7BBE79B9."
"png[10000000000001600000004C7BBE79B9_png]"
msgstr ""
"image:images/10000000000001600000004C7BBE79B9."
"png[10000000000001600000004C7BBE79B9_png]"

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:563
msgid ""
"Click on the 'Global Design Rules' tab and set 'Min track width' to 0.01'. "
"Click the OK button to commit your changes and close the Design Rules Editor "
"window."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:568
msgid ""
"Now we will import the netlist file. Click on the 'Read Netlist' icon image:"
"images/netlist.png[netlist_png] on the top toolbar. Click on the 'Browse "
"Netlist Files' button, select 'tute1.net' in the File selection dialogue, "
"and click on 'Read Current Netlist'. Then click the 'Close' button."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:570
msgid ""
"All components should now be visible in the top left hand corner just above "
"the page. Scroll up if you cannot see them."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:573
msgid ""
"Select all components with the mouse and move them to the middle of the "
"board. If necessary you can zoom in and out while you move the components."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:579
msgid ""
"All components are connected via a thin group of wires called __ratsnest__. "
"Make sure that the 'Hide board ratsnest' button image:images/"
"general_ratsnest.png[general_ratsnest_png] is pressed. In this way you can "
"see the ratsnest linking all components. NOTE: The tool-tip is backwards; "
"pressing this button actually displays the ratsnest."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:587
msgid ""
"You can move each component by hovering over it and pressing the g key. "
"Click where you want to place them. Move all components around until you "
"minimise the number of wire crossovers. NOTE: If instead of grabbing the "
"components (with the g key ) you move them around using the m key you will "
"later note that you lose the track connection (the same occurs in the "
"schematic editor). Bottom line, always use the g key option.  image:"
"images/10000000000001FD000001B15F2BA74A."
"png[10000000000001FD000001B15F2BA74A_png]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:592
msgid ""
"If the ratsnest disappears or the screen gets messy, right click and click "
"'Redraw view'. Note how one pin of the 100 ohm resistor is connected to pin "
"6 of the PIC component. This is the result of the labelling method used to "
"connect pins. Labels are often preferred to actual wires because they make "
"the schematic much less messy."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:598
msgid ""
"Now we will define the edge of the PCB. Select 'PCB Edges' from the drop "
"down menu in the top toolbar. Click on the 'Add graphic line or polygon' "
"icon image:images/add_dashed_line.png[add_dashed_line_png] on the right "
"toolbar. Trace around the edge of the board, clicking at each corner, and "
"remember to leave a small gap between the edge of the green and the edge of "
"the PCB."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:601
msgid ""
"Next, connect up all the wires except GND. In fact, we will connect all GND "
"connections in one go using a ground plane placed on the bottom copper "
"(called __Back__) of the board."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:605
msgid ""
"Now we must choose which copper layer we want to work on. Select 'Front' in "
"the drag down menu on the top toolbar. This is the top copper layer.  image:"
"images/10000000000000D30000010D5271F1F8."
"png[10000000000000D30000010D5271F1F8_png]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:610
msgid ""
"If you decide, for instance, to do a 4 layer PCB instead, go to *Design "
"Rules* -> *Layers Setup* and change 'Copper Layers' to 4. In the 'Layers' "
"table you can name layers and decide what they can be used for.  Notice that "
"there are very useful presets that can be selected via the 'Preset Layers "
"Groupings' menu."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:617
msgid ""
"Click on the 'Add Tracks and vias' icon image:images/add_tracks."
"png[add_tracks_png] on the right toolbar. Click on pin 1 of 'J1' and run a "
"track to pad 'R2'. Double-click to set the point where the track will end. "
"The width of this track will be the default 0.203 mm. You can change the "
"track width from the drop-down menu in the top toolbar. Mind that by default "
"you have only one track width available. image:images/pcbnew_1."
"png[pcbnew_1_png]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:623
msgid ""
"If you would like to add more track widths g o to: *Design Rules* -> *Design "
"Rules* -> *Global Design Rules* tab and at the bottom right of this window "
"add any other width you would like to have available. You can then choose "
"the widths of the track from the drop-down menu while you lay out your "
"board. See the example below.  image:images/1000000000000169000001178613965A."
"png[1000000000000169000001178613965A_png]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:629
msgid ""
"Alternatively, you can add a Net Class in which you specify a set of "
"options. Go to *Design Rules* -> *Design Rules* -> *Net Classes Editor* and "
"add a new class called 'power'. Change the track width from 8 mil (indicated "
"as 0.0080) to 24 mil (indicated as 0.0240). Next, add everything but ground "
"to the ‘power’ class (select 'default' at left and 'power' at right and use "
"the arrows)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:632
msgid ""
"If you want to change the grid size, *Right click* -> **Grid Select**. Be "
"sure to select the appropriate grid size before or after laying down the "
"components and connecting them together with tracks."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:635 Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:1052
msgid ""
"Considering, for instance, that a 0.8mm BGA component has a pin to pin "
"distance of about 30 mil (0.8mm), **it is generally commendable to set a "
"grid size of 5 mil when you route**."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: Getting_Started_in_KiCad.adoc:638
msgid ""
"Repeat this process until all wires, except pin 3 of J1, are connected. Your "
"board should look like the example below.  image:"
"images/10000000000001F8000001B32F1802F1."
"png[10000000000001F8000001B32F1802F1_png]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
